  kicker="SECURITY HARNESS · AI AGENTS"
  title="AEGIS."
  dek="A deterministic security evaluation harness for tool-using agents."
  role="Sole author"
  period="2026"
  status="Open source · MIT"
  read="≈ 5 min"
  description="Reproducible, layered defense evaluation for tool-using agent workflows — policy → keyword → semantic guards, every decision traced."
>

  <!-- 01 Brief -->
  <article class="chapter">
    <div class="chapter-num mono">
      <span>CHAPTER</span>
      <span class="big">01</span>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kicker mono">THE BRIEF</div>
      <h2>Agent security needs reproducible numbers, not anecdotes.</h2>
      <p class="lede">A tool-using agent fails differently from a chatbot. Most published evaluations treat the two the same — accuracy on a benchmark, a few hand-picked exploits, no shared apparatus. The result is that "this defense works" is a vibe, not a measurement.</p>
      <div class="body">
        <p>AEGIS exists to make defense comparisons boring. Same scenarios. Same payloads. Same scoring. Different guard stack — and a number you can defend in a code review. The harness is deterministic on purpose: every run produces the same trace from the same config, so a delta between two runs is a defense delta, not noise.</p>
        <p>The first version uses a deterministic demo runner instead of a live LLM. That is a feature, not a shortcut: it removes model variance from the experiment, exposes the guard logic on its own terms, and keeps the host machine safe while exploring tool-misuse scenarios.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- 02 Approach -->
  <article class="chapter">
    <div class="chapter-num mono">
      <span>CHAPTER</span>
      <span class="big">02</span>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kicker mono">THE APPROACH</div>
      <h2>Layered defense, observable at every step.</h2>
      <div class="body">
        <p>Every tool proposal flows through a stack of guards before it can run. <strong>Policy</strong> enforces the allowlist — which tools may be invoked at all. <strong>Keyword</strong> rejects the obvious high-risk patterns. <strong>Semantic</strong> compares the payload against a corpus of known attack shapes using n-gram cosine similarity — no heavy ML, no black box. Anything that passes all three reaches the (mocked) tool. Anything that doesn't lands in the trace as a typed block event.</p>
        <p>Tool execution itself is mocked. Simulated email exfiltration, simulated shell, simulated network egress — never a real side effect. The harness is a security lab, not a deploy target.</p>
      </div>

